(PART) Part: Basics

Entering and cleaning data

There are four basic steps as you prepare to analyze data in R:

  1. Identify where the data is (If it's on your computer, which directory? If it's online, what's the url?)
  2. Read data into R (read.csv, read.table) using the file path you figured out in step 1
  3. Check to make sure the data came in correctly (dim, head, tail, str)
  4. Clean the data up

Directories and pathnames

Working directory

You can figure out which directory R is working in by running the command getwd(). For example,

getwd()
#> [1] "/Users/matilde/Documents/teaching/corsi/MLDA/bookdown-mlda/slides"

You can set a new working directory using pathnames and the setwd() function. For example,

setwd("~")
getwd()
#> [1] "/Users/matilde"

Finally, you can use R Projects from within RStudio. The working directory is the project directory (the directory in which the .Rproj file is stored).

File and directory pathnames

Pathnames are the directions for getting to a directory or file stored on your computer.

You can use one of two types of pathnames:

  • Relative pathname: How to get to the file or directory from your current working directory
  • Absolute pathname: How to get to the file or directory from anywhere on the computer

Absolute pathnames give the full directions starting all the way at the root directory. For example, the daily_show_guests.csv file in the data directory has the absolute pathname:

"/Users/matilde/Documents/teaching/corsi/MLDA/bookdown-mlda/data/daily_show_guests.csv"

You can use this absolute pathname to read this file in using read.csv.

file_path <- "/Users/matilde/Documents/teaching/corsi/MLDA/bookdown-mlda/data/daily_show_guests.csv"
daily_show <- read.csv(file_path)

The relative pathname depends on your current working directory.

As an example of a relative pathname, say you're working in the directory bookdown-mlda and you want to read in the daily_show_guests.csv file in the data subdirectory. Therefore, the relative pathname would be:

"data/daily_show_guests.csv"

You can use this relative pathname to tell R where to find and read in the file:

daily_show <- read.csv("data/daily_show_guests.csv", header = TRUE, skip = 4)

There are some abbreviations for pathnames:

Shorthand Meaning
~ Home directory
. Current working directory
.. One directory up from current working directory
../.. Two directories up from current working directory

If you're getting errors reading in files, it's often helpful to use list.files() to make sure the file in question is in the directory that the relative pathname you're using is directing R to.

list.files()
#>  [1] "_output.yml"                   "00-course_info.html"          
#>  [3] "00-course_info.pdf"            "00-course_info.Rmd"           
#>  [5] "01-prelim.pdf"                 "01-Rprelim.html"              
#>  [7] "01-Rprelim.Rmd"                "02-overview.html"             
#>  [9] "02-overview.pdf"               "02-overview.Rmd"              
#> [11] "03-databasics_smaller.html"    "03-databasics.html"           
#> [13] "03-databasics.pdf"             "03-databasics.Rmd"            
#> [15] "04-exploringdata_smaller.html" "04-exploringdata.html"        
#> [17] "04-exploringdata.pdf"          "04-exploringdata.Rmd"         
#> [19] "05-regressionmodels.html"      "05-regressionmodels.pdf"      
#> [21] "05-regressionmodels.Rmd"       "custom_template.html"         
#> [23] "shiny-slides.css"

Diversion: paste

The paste() function takes, as inputs, a series of different character strings and pastes them together in a single character string. For example:

paste("Sunday", "Monday", "Tuesday")
#> [1] "Sunday Monday Tuesday"

The paste() function has an option called sep = that indicates what is the separator. The default is a space. For example, if you wanted to paste without spaces, you could use sep = "":

paste("Sunday", "Monday", "Tuesday", sep = "")
#> [1] "SundayMondayTuesday"

As a shortcut, you could achieve the same thing using the paste0 function.

paste0("Sunday", "Monday", "Tuesday")
#> [1] "SundayMondayTuesday"

Reading data into R

Some of the types of data files that R can read in:

  • Flat files (much more about these in just a minute)
  • Files from other statistical packages (SAS, Excel, Stata, SPSS)
  • Tables on webpages (e.g., the table on ebola outbreaks near the end of this Wikipedia page)
  • Data in a database (e.g., MySQL, Oracle)
  • Data in JSON and XML formats
  • Geographic shapefiles
  • Data through APIs (e.g., GoogleMaps, Twitter, many government agencies)

Reading local flat files

Flat files basically are files that you can open using a text editor. Most flat files come in two general categories:

  1. Fixed width files

  2. Delimited files

  • ".csv": Comma-separated values
  • ".tab", ".tsv": Tab-separated values
  • Other possible delimiters: colon, semicolon, pipe ("|")

For example,

Course            Number          Day          Time
Intro to Epi      501             M/W/F        9:00-9:50
Advanced Epi      521             T/Th         1:00-2:15
Course, Number, Day, Time
"Intro to Epi", 501, "M/W/F", "9:00-9:50"
"Advanced Epi", 521, "T/Th", "1:00-2:15"

If the file is delimited, you can use the read.table family of functions. This family of functions includes several specialized functions.

Function Separator Decimial point
read.table comma period
read.csv comma period
read.csv2 semi-colon comma
read.delim tab period
read.delim2 tab period

For example, to read in the Ebola data, which is comma-delimited, you could either use read.table or use read.csv. Complete the code on your own:

# These two calls do the same thing
# ebola <- read.table("data/country_timeseries.csv" ..???..)
# ebola <- read.csv("data/country_timeseries.csv" ..???..)

Some of the interesting parameters with the read.table family of functions are:

Option Description
sep What is the delimiter in the data?
skip How many lines of the start of the file should you skip?
header Does the first line you read give column names?
as.is Should you bring in strings as characters, not factors?
nrows How many rows do you want to read in?
na.strings How are missing values coded?

Remember that you can always find out more about a function by looking at its help file. For example, check out ?read.table and ?read.fwf.

The read_* functions

The read.table family of functions are part of base R. There is a newer package called readr that has a family of read_* functions. These functions are very similar, but have some more sensible defaults.

  • Work better with large datasets: faster, includes progress bar
  • Have more sensible defaults (e.g., characters default to characters, not factors)

Functions in the read_* family include:

  • read_csv, read_tsv (specific delimiters)
  • read_delim, read_table (generic)
  • read_fwf
  • read_log
  • read_lines

library(readr)
daily_show <- read_csv(paste0(proj_path,"data/daily_show_guests.csv"), 
                       skip = 4)
#> Parsed with column specification:
#> cols(
#>   YEAR = col_integer(),
#>   GoogleKnowlege_Occupation = col_character(),
#>   Show = col_character(),
#>   Group = col_character(),
#>   Raw_Guest_List = col_character()
#> )

The "tidyverse"

The readr package is a member of the tidyverse of packages.

Most were developed in part or full by Hadley Wickham and others at RStudio.

You can use the tidyverse package to download all tidyverse packages at one.

Reading online flat files

With the read_* family of functions, you can data from the web for flat files from a non-secure webpage and for files from a secure webpage (including GitHub and Dropbox). With the read.table family of functions, you can read in online flat files from non-secure webpages only.

For example, to read in the tab-separated file saved at this web address you can run:

url <- paste0("http://www2.unil.ch/comparativegenometrics",
              "/docs/NC_006368.txt")
# write the code for reading in:

ld_genetics[1:5, 1:4]
#>    pos  nA  nC  nG
#> 1  500 307 153 192
#> 2 1500 310 169 207
#> 3 2500 319 167 177
#> 4 3500 373 164 168
#> 5 4500 330 175 224

To read in data from this GitHub repository of Ebola data you can run:

url <- paste0("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/cmrivers/",
              "ebola/master/country_timeseries.csv")
# write the code for reading in:

ebola[1:3, 1:3]
#>       Date Day Cases_Guinea
#> 1 1/5/2015 289         2776
#> 2 1/4/2015 288         2775
#> 3 1/3/2015 287         2769

Saving and loading R objects

You can save an R object you've created as an .RData file using the save function:

save(ebola, file = "Ebola.RData")
list.files(pattern = "E")
##  [1] "Ebola.RData"

Then, you can re-load it later using the load function. For example,

rm(ebola)
ls()
## [1] "ld_genetics" "my_dir"      "url"
load("Ebola.RData")
ls()
## [1] "ebola"       "ld_genetics" "my_dir"      "url"

Reading other file types

There are two "tidyverse" packages – readxl and haven – that allow you to read in files from the following formats:

File type Function Package
Excel read_excel readxl
SAS read_sas haven
SPSS read_spss haven
Stata `read_stata haven

Data cleaning

Here are some of the most common data-cleaning tasks:

Task dplyr function
Renaming columns rename
Filtering to certain rows filter

Adding or changing columns mutate

The dplyr package is a member of the tidyverse of packages.

Ill use example data listing guests to the Daily Show.

library(dplyr)
daily_show <- read_csv("data/daily_show_guests.csv", skip = 4)
head(daily_show)

Renaming columns

A first step is often re-naming the columns of the dataframe. It can be hard to work with a column name that:

  • is long
  • includes spaces
  • includes upper case

You can check out the column names for a dataframe using the colnames function. Several of the column names in daily_show have some of these issues:

colnames(daily_show)
#> [1] "YEAR"                      "GoogleKnowlege_Occupation"
#> [3] "Show"                      "Group"                    
#> [5] "Raw_Guest_List"

To rename these columns, use rename. The basic syntax is:

## Generic code
rename(dataframe,
       new_column_name_1 = old_column_name_1,
       new_column_name_2 = old_column_name_2)

To rename columns in the daily_show data, for example, you would run:

daily_show <- rename(daily_show,
                     year = YEAR,
                     job = GoogleKnowlege_Occupation,
                     date = Show,
                     category = Group,
                     guest_name = Raw_Guest_List)
head(daily_show, 3)
#> # A tibble: 3 x 5
#>    year                job    date category      guest_name
#>   <int>              <chr>   <chr>    <chr>           <chr>
#> 1  1999              actor 1/11/99   Acting  Michael J. Fox
#> 2  1999           Comedian 1/12/99   Comedy Sandra Bernhard
#> 3  1999 television actress 1/13/99   Acting   Tracey Ullman

Selecting columns

Next, you may want to select only some columns of the dataframe. You can use the select function from dplyr. The basic structure of this command is:

## Generic code
select(dataframe, column_name_1, column_name_2, ...)

For example, to select all columns in daily_show except year (since that information is already included in date), run:

select(daily_show, job, date, category, guest_name)
#> # A tibble: 2,693 x 4
#>                   job    date category       guest_name
#>                 <chr>   <chr>    <chr>            <chr>
#>  1              actor 1/11/99   Acting   Michael J. Fox
#>  2           Comedian 1/12/99   Comedy  Sandra Bernhard
#>  3 television actress 1/13/99   Acting    Tracey Ullman
#>  4       film actress 1/14/99   Acting Gillian Anderson
#>  5              actor 1/18/99   Acting David Alan Grier
#>  6              actor 1/19/99   Acting  William Baldwin
#>  7    Singer-lyricist 1/20/99 Musician    Michael Stipe
#>  8              model 1/21/99    Media   Carmen Electra
#>  9              actor 1/25/99   Acting  Matthew Lillard
#> 10  stand-up comedian 1/26/99   Comedy      David Cross
#> # ... with 2,683 more rows
daily_show <- select(daily_show, -year)

As a reminder, we could have selected these columns using square bracket indexing, too:

daily_show ..??..

the select function has some cool extra options, including:

  • Selecting all columns that start / end with or contain a certain pattern

Slicing to certain rows

The dplyr package has a function to limit a dataframe to certain rows by row number, called slice. That function has the syntax:

## Generic code
slice(dataframe, starting_row:ending_row)

For example, to print the first three rows of the daily_show data, yo can run:

slice(daily_show, 1:3)
#> # A tibble: 3 x 4
#>                  job    date category      guest_name
#>                <chr>   <chr>    <chr>           <chr>
#> 1              actor 1/11/99   Acting  Michael J. Fox
#> 2           Comedian 1/12/99   Comedy Sandra Bernhard
#> 3 television actress 1/13/99   Acting   Tracey Ullman

Arranging rows

There is also a function, arrange, you can use to re-order the rows in a dataframe. The syntax for this function is:

## Generic code
arrange(dataframe, column_to_order_by)

For example, we could reorder the daily_show data alphabetically by the values in the category column with the following call:

daily_show <- arrange(daily_show, category)
head(daily_show, 3)
#> # A tibble: 3 x 4
#>         job    date category        guest_name
#>       <chr>   <chr>    <chr>             <chr>
#> 1 professor 10/3/01 Academic  Stephen S. Morse
#> 2 Professor 12/3/01 Academic   Nadine Strossen
#> 3 Historian 11/4/03 Academic Michael Beschloss

Or by descending date:

daily_show <- arrange(daily_show, desc(date))
head(daily_show, 3)
#> # A tibble: 3 x 4
#>                     job   date   category         guest_name
#>                   <chr>  <chr>      <chr>              <chr>
#> 1 United States Senator 9/9/14 Politician Kirsten Gillibrand
#> 2            Journalist 9/9/13      Media         Sheri Fink
#> 3             Columnist 9/9/10      Media      Meghan McCain

Filtering to certain rows

Next, you might want to filter the dataset down so that it only includes certain rows.

You can use the filter function from dplyr. The syntax is:

## Generic code
filter(dataframe, logical statement)

The logical statement in this call gives the condition that a row must meet to be included in the output data frame.

For example, if you want to create a data frame that only includes guests who were scientists, you can run:

scientists <- filter(daily_show, category == "Science")
head(scientists)
#> # A tibble: 6 x 4
#>              job    date category          guest_name
#>            <chr>   <chr>    <chr>               <chr>
#> 1   neurosurgeon  9/7/11  Science    Dr. Sanjay Gupta
#> 2         doctor  9/6/05  Science     Dr. Marc Siegel
#> 3 Astrophysicist  9/4/13  Science         Mario Livio
#> 4 Astrophysicist 7/23/07  Science Neil deGrasse Tyson
#> 5    Neurologist 6/29/09  Science        Oliver Sacks
#> 6      physician 6/23/10  Science  Dr. Connie Mariano

Some of the most commonly used R's logical operators are:

Operator Meaning Example
== equals category == "Acting"
!= does not equal category != "Comedy
%in% is in category %in% c("Academic", "Science")
is.na() is NA is.na(job)
!is.na() is not NA !is.na(job)
& and year == 2015 & category == "Academic"
| or year == 2015 | category == "Academic"

Add or change columns

You can change a column or add a new column using the mutate function from the dplyr package. That function has the syntax:

# Generic code
mutate(dataframe,
       changed_column = function(changed_column),
       new_column = function(other arguments))

For example, the job column in daily_show sometimes uses upper case and sometimes does not:

head(unique(daily_show$job), 10)
#>  [1] "United States Senator" "Journalist"           
#>  [3] "Columnist"             "united states senator"
#>  [5] "actress"               "journalist"           
#>  [7] NA                      "neurosurgeon"         
#>  [9] "Consultant"            "actor"

To make all the observations in the job column lowercase, use the tolower function within a mutate function:

mutate(daily_show, job = tolower(job))
#> # A tibble: 2,693 x 4
#>                      job   date   category         guest_name
#>                    <chr>  <chr>      <chr>              <chr>
#>  1 united states senator 9/9/14 Politician Kirsten Gillibrand
#>  2            journalist 9/9/13      Media         Sheri Fink
#>  3             columnist 9/9/10      Media      Meghan McCain
#>  4 united states senator 9/9/03 Politician         Al Franken
#>  5               actress 9/9/02     Acting    Lorraine Bracco
#>  6               actress 9/8/11     Acting   Marion Cotillard
#>  7 united states senator 9/8/10 Politician          Tim Kaine
#>  8            journalist 9/8/05      Media     Brian Williams
#>  9                  <NA> 9/7/12       <NA>               none
#> 10          neurosurgeon 9/7/11    Science   Dr. Sanjay Gupta
#> # ... with 2,683 more rows

Piping

A powerful strategy for solving complex problems is to combine many simple pieces.

So far, these dplyr functions have been used one at a time to clean up the data, reassigning the dataframe object at each step. However, there's a trick called "piping" that will let you clean up your code a bit.

Without piping, you have to reassign the dataframe object at each step of this cleaning if you want the changes saved in the object:

daily_show <-read_csv("data/daily_show_guests.csv",
                      skip = 4)
daily_show <- rename(daily_show,
                     job = GoogleKnowlege_Occupation,
                     date = Show,
                     category = Group,
                     guest_name = Raw_Guest_List)
daily_show <- select(daily_show, -YEAR)
daily_show <- mutate(daily_show, job = tolower(job))
daily_show <- filter(daily_show, category == "Science")

Piping pipes the dataframe created right before the pipe (%>%) into the function right after the pipe. With piping, therefore, the same data cleaning looks like:

daily_show <-read_csv(paste0(proj_path,"data/daily_show_guests.csv"),
                      skip = 4) %>%
  rename(job = GoogleKnowlege_Occupation,
         date = Show,
         category = Group,
         guest_name = Raw_Guest_List) %>%
  select(-YEAR) %>%
  mutate(job = tolower(job)) %>%
  filter(category == "Science")

Base R equivalents to dplyr functions

All of these dplyr functions have alternatives in base R:

dplyr Base R equivalent
rename Reassign colnames
select Square bracket indexing
filter subset
mutate Use $ to change / create columns
